    How customer reviews and ratings work

    Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings, help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

    To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyses reviews to verify trustworthiness.

    • ab..c
      5.0 out of 5 stars Great hardware and price.
      Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 6 June 2016
      Colour Name: BlackSize Name: 64GBStyle Name: SingleVerified Purchase
      * Physical

      This 64Gb thumb drive is small physically, but it fits into standard USB 2.0 connections very easily. It's shaped into a gentle shape of your thumb. If you need to know, when you look into the port on your computer, the USB 2.0 ports have a white colour to make the user aware of the difference when compared with blue for later USB 3.0 ports

      * Performance

      It's of a capacity that would encourage the much faster USB 3.0 connectivity to be more attractive. The USB 3.0 is supposed to be ten times faster uploading and downloading files than the earlier USB 2.0 ports. But in reality is around 4 or 5 times more rapid than for USB 2.0. So if you're using this capacity of flash drives on a regular basis, have USB 3.0 hardware, and are throwing around very big file sizes on your system, I would consider upgrading to USB 3.0 thumb drives.

      * Main usage

      I have bought this thumb drive to serve as a 'Recovery Drive' for Windows 10. The current requirement to create a recovery drive is it's at least USB 2.0 and has around 32Gb free capacity. So I overestimated the capacity requirement - just in case - and bought this 64Gb. The drive is made to have this 64GB drive but creating this recovery drive permanently reduced its capacity to 32GB. This is to make it bootable as required. When I did the first recovery drive for Windows 8.0, I thought the copy of the whole of drive C: would be placed on a thumb drive, so i bought a 128Gb pen drive. This was actually permanently reduced to 32 Gig too, so even when i formatted this USB 2.0 drive, the 128 Gig was from then still permanently reduced to 32 Gig!

      * Summary

      This hardware has a very high capacity and almost enough to be thrown away cost. If you have USB 3.0 and can use this size regularly, this makes sense to use this standard. But if you're willing to wait for files to upload and download, you can save yourself the cost and use these USB 2.0 thumb drives. My main point is it's a lot cheaper to buy through Amazon than buying through supermarkets as when you compare cost to capacity it's Amazon that is attractive!
